    </div>

    <p>Sugar-free creatine gummies use alternative sweeteners — allulose (the current gold standard for keto-friendly sweetening with a near-zero glycemic index), monk fruit extract, stevia, or erythritol — to maintain palatability without sugar. The creatine itself functions identically regardless of the sweetener used, because creatine absorption occurs in the small intestine through specific sodium-dependent creatine transporters (CrT) that are unaffected by the type of sweetener present. While some research suggests insulin (stimulated by sugar) may enhance creatine uptake via GLUT4 transporters, the practical difference is negligible — consistent daily dosing achieves full muscle creatine saturation within 3-4 weeks regardless of sugar co-ingestion.</p>

    <p>The sugar-free creatine gummy category has matured significantly since 2024, with several brands now delivering formulations that taste comparable to their sugar-containing counterparts while maintaining zero sugar, zero net carbs, and keto-certified status. The key differentiators are the specific creatine form (monohydrate vs. HCl vs. buffered), the sweetener system (allulose vs. stevia vs. erythritol), and the creatine dose per serving (which determines how many gummies you need daily to reach the 3-5g target).</p>

