    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Sugar-Free Creatine Gummies</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Are sugar-free creatine gummies effective?</summary><p>Equally effective as sugar-containing versions. Creatine absorption depends on CrT transporters, not sugar content. Consistent 3-5g daily dosing achieves full muscle saturation in 3-4 weeks regardless of sweetener type.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What sweeteners are used in sugar-free creatine gummies?</summary><p>Allulose (gold standard for keto, near-zero GI), erythritol (zero calories but may cause digestive issues), stevia (natural, zero calories), monk fruit (natural, zero calories), and sucralose (artificial). Prefer allulose or monk fruit for best tolerance.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Do sugar-free creatine gummies kick you out of ketosis?</summary><p>No. Formulations with allulose, stevia, monk fruit, or erythritol have zero glycemic impact. Always check labels — some "sugar-free" products use maltitol (moderate GI). Creatine itself has zero carbs and zero calories.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How many sugar-free creatine gummies do I need daily?</summary><p>Depends on creatine per serving: 1.5g per serving needs 2-3 servings; 2.5g needs 2 servings; 5g needs 1 serving. Target 3-5g total daily creatine. More gummies means more sweetener exposure — consider digestive tolerance.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Are sugar-free creatine gummies worth the extra cost?</summary><p>Worth it for strict keto/low-carb athletes, calorie-trackers, and those with diabetes or insulin resistance. For general fitness without dietary restrictions, standard creatine gummies are equally effective at lower cost.</p></details>

